[[File:Sean_McVay_2019_(cropped2).jpg|thumb|right|[[Sean McVay]], the 28th and current head coach of the [[Los Angeles Rams]]|alt=Sean McVay on field during a team practice in 2019]]

The [[Los Angeles Rams]] are a professional American football team based in the [[Greater Los Angeles]] area of California. The Rams have competed in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) since 1937, one year after their formation in [[Cleveland, Ohio]] as a charter member of the [[American Football League (1936)|second incarnation of the American Football League]].<ref name="Cleveland">{{cite web |title=Cleveland Rams: Encyclopedia of Cleveland History |date=March 10, 2021 |url=https://case.edu/ech/articles/c/cleveland-rams |publisher=[[Case Western Reserve University]] |access-date=January 23, 2024 |archive-date=June 6, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230606022005/https://case.edu/ech/articles/c/cleveland-rams |url-status=live }}</ref> The team moved to [[Los Angeles]] in 1946 where they became the city's first professional sports team.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Markazi |first1=Arash |title=Column: Rams' New Uniforms Don't Fit with their Iconic Brand |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/rams/story/2020-05-13/column-rams-new-uniforms-dont-fit-with-iconic-brand |access-date=March 27, 2022 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 13, 2020 |archive-date=September 15, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220915012500/https://www.latimes.com/sports/rams/story/2020-05-13/column-rams-new-uniforms-dont-fit-with-iconic-brand |url-status=live }}</ref> They first played their home games at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]] before moving to [[Anaheim, California]] in 1980, where they played their home games at [[Angel Stadium|Anaheim Stadium]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Banks |first1=Don |title=L.A. Coliseum Has Back-to-the-Future Homecoming Awaiting Rams |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2016/03/15/rams-relocation-los-angeles-memorial-coliseum |access-date=January 26, 2024 |magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=March 15, 2016 |archive-date=January 26, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240126001049/https://www.si.com/nfl/2016/03/15/rams-relocation-los-angeles-memorial-coliseum |url-status=live }}</ref> The Rams moved to [[St. Louis]], Missouri in 1995, and remained there for two decades until they returned to Los Angeles after the [[2015 NFL season]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Farmer |first1=Sam |last2=Fenno |first2=Nathan |title=NFL Will Return to Los Angeles for 2016 Season |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/nfl/la-sp-nfl-la-chargers-rams-20160113-story.html |access-date=February 28, 2016 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=January 12, 2016 |archive-date=February 28, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220228114422/https://www.latimes.com/sports/nfl/la-sp-nfl-la-chargers-rams-20160113-story.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Currently, they are members of the [[NFC West|Western Division]] of the [[National Football Conference]] (NFC) and play their home games at [[SoFi Stadium]] in [[Inglewood, California]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Los Angeles Rams Scores, Stats, and Highlights |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/lar/los-angeles-rams |access-date=March 27, 2022 |agency=[[ESPN]] |archive-date=March 27, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220327004416/https://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/lar/los-angeles-rams |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Profile">{{cite web |title=Los Angeles Rams–NFL Football Operations |url=https://operations.nfl.com/learn-the-game/nfl-basics/team-histories/national-football-conference/west/los-angeles-rams/ |publisher=[[National Football League]] |access-date=March 27, 2022 |archive-date=April 13, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220413183216/https://operations.nfl.com/learn-the-game/nfl-basics/team-histories/national-football-conference/west/los-angeles-rams/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

From among the 28 head coaches throughout the team's history, [[Sid Gillman]], [[George Allen (American football coach)|George Allen]], and [[Dick Vermeil]] were inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in recognition of their contributions as coaches. [[Joe Stydahar]] and [[Bob Waterfield]] were also inducted into the Hall of Fame, although they were recognized for their contributions as players, not coaches.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro Football Hall of Fame Inductees |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/hof/ |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=March 24, 2022 |archive-date=May 7, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130507163808/http://www.pro-football-reference.com/hof/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Five coaches have been recognized as coach of the year by major news organizations: [[Adam Walsh (American football)|Adam Walsh]] in 1945, [[Hamp Pool]] in 1952, Allen in 1967, [[Chuck Knox]] in 1973, Vermeil in 1999, and [[Sean McVay]] in 2017.{{efn|Attributed to multiple references:<ref name="SI 1985">{{cite magazine |last1=Flood |first1=Gay |title=19th Hole: The Readers Take Over |url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1985/02/18/19th-hole-the-readers-take-over |access-date=July 21, 2023 |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=February 18, 1985 |archive-date=January 25, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240125214238/https://vault.si.com/vault/1985/02/18/19th-hole-the-readers-take-over |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="APCOY">{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/awards/ap-coach-of-the-year.htm | publisher = [[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] | access-date = January 8, 2024 | title = AP Coach of the Year Winners | archive-date = January 3, 2022 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20220103180612/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/awards/ap-coach-of-the-year.htm | url-status = live }}</ref><ref name="SNCOY">{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/awards/sporting-news-coach-of-the-year-award.htm | publisher = Pro-Football-Reference.com | title = Sporting News Coach of the Year Winners | access-date = January 12, 2024 | archive-date = June 2, 2023 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20230602192053/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/awards/sporting-news-coach-of-the-year-award.htm | url-status = live }}</ref><ref name="UPICOY">{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/awards/upi-coach-of-the-year-award.htm | access-date = January 12, 2024 | publisher = Pro-Football-Reference.com | title = UPI Coach of the Year Winners | archive-date = January 12, 2024 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20240112211652/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/awards/upi-coach-of-the-year-award.htm | url-status = live }}</ref>}}

==History==
[[Damon Wetzel]] was the Rams' first head coach in 1936. Although the team was scheduled to play against the [[Boston Shamrocks (AFL)|Boston Shamrocks]] in the AFL's Championship Game, the Shamrocks were forced to forfeit the game after unpaid players on that team declined to participate in it.<ref name="Cleveland" /> The Rams then moved to the NFL the following year and hired [[Hugo Bezdek]] as their new head coach. During his tenure, however, he coached the team to only a single win in his first year.<ref name="Rams Coaches">{{cite web |title=Los Angeles Rams Coaches |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/ram/coaches.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=December 10, 2022 |archive-date=January 13, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230113214923/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/ram/coaches.htm |url-status=live }}</ref> Bezdek was later fired after three games to start the 1938 NFL season and was replaced by assistant coach [[Art Lewis]] for the remainder of the year.<ref name="NYT Bezdek">{{cite news |title=Cleveland Rams Drop Bezdek |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1938/09/29/archives/cleveland-rams-drop-bezdek.html |access-date=February 8, 2022 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 29, 1938 |archive-date=January 25, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240125211401/https://www.nytimes.com/1938/09/29/archives/cleveland-rams-drop-bezdek.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The Rams continued to struggle under subsequent head coaches [[Dutch Clark]] and [[Aldo Donelli]], none of whom had a winning percentage of over .400.<ref name="Rams Coaches" /> The team finally found success under [[Adam Walsh (American football)|Adam Walsh]], who guided the Rams to the franchise's first [[History of the National Football League championship|NFL Championship]] in [[1945 NFL Championship Game|1945]]. Walsh remained head coach during the team's relocation to Los Angeles in 1946 before being replaced by [[Bob Snyder (American football)|Bob Snyder]] in 1947. Snyder's tenure turned out to be short due to then-owner [[Dan Reeves (American football executive)|Dan Reeves]] firing him prior to the start of the [[1949 NFL season]] and replacing him with newly-minted advisor [[Clark Shaughnessy]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Shrake |first1=Edwin |title=A Private Eye on the New Rams |url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1966/10/03/a-private-eye-on-the-new-rams |access-date=January 24, 2024 |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=October 3, 1966 |archive-date=January 28, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240128084022/https://vault.si.com/vault/1966/10/03/a-private-eye-on-the-new-rams |url-status=live }}</ref> For the next three seasons, Shaughnessy and his successor [[Joe Stydahar]], who was previously the team's line coach, led the team to three consecutive playoff berths, including the franchise's second NFL Championship in [[1951 NFL Championship Game|1951]].<ref name="Rams Coaches" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Harrison |first1=Scott |title=From the Archives: The L.A. Rams Beat the Cleveland Browns for 1951 Championship |url=https://www.latimes.com/visuals/photography/la-me-fw-archives-la-rams-beat-cleveland-browns-for-1951-championship-20171107-story.html |access-date=January 24, 2024 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=January 5, 2018 |archive-date=January 26, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240126072337/https://www.latimes.com/visuals/photography/la-me-fw-archives-la-rams-beat-cleveland-browns-for-1951-championship-20171107-story.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The following season, however, tensions between Stydahar and backfield coach [[Hamp Pool]] led the former to resign and the latter succeeding him as head coach.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Larkin |first1=Will |title=Ranking the 100 Best Bears Players Ever: No. 15, Joe Stydahar |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/bears/history/ct-spt-bears-best-players-joe-stydahar-20190822-zpj5fbsvonabjeobkoedtbz56e-story.html |access-date=January 23, 2024 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=August 22, 2019 |archive-date=January 26, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240126033426/https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/bears/history/ct-spt-bears-best-players-joe-stydahar-20190822-zpj5fbsvonabjeobkoedtbz56e-story.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Pool led the Rams to a playoff berth as did his successor [[Sid Gillman]].<ref name="Rams Coaches" />

After Gillman left to coach the [[Los Angeles Chargers]] in the newly-formed [[American Football League|third incarnation of the American Football League]], the team languished from 1960 to 1965 under head coaches [[Bob Waterfield]] and [[Harland Svare]] whose tenures yielded winning percentages no higher than .279.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gillman Resigns as Chargers' Coach |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/11/23/archives/gillman-resigns-as-chargers-coach-departs-after-talk-with-club.html |access-date=March 24, 2022 |work=The New York Times |date=November 23, 1971 |archive-date=January 26, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240126201723/https://www.nytimes.com/1971/11/23/archives/gillman-resigns-as-chargers-coach-departs-after-talk-with-club.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Rams Coaches" /> In 1966, the Rams hired [[George Allen (American football coach)|George Allen]] as head coach where he led the team to two playoff berths in five seasons. After Allen stepped down following the [[1970 NFL season]], [[Tommy Prothro]] was hired as head coach and served for two seasons until he was replaced with [[Chuck Knox]] by new owner [[Carroll Rosenbloom]]. From 1973 to 1980, Knox and his successor [[Ray Malavasi]] guided the team to seven straight NFC West division titles and eight consecutive playoff berths including an appearance in [[Super Bowl XIV]] at the end of the [[1979 NFL season]], the first in team history. After the 1982 season concluded, Malvasi was replaced by former [[USC Trojans football|USC]] head coach [[John Robinson (American football coach)|John Robinson]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Robinson Is Named Coach of Rams |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/02/15/sports/robinson-is-named-coach-of-rams.html |access-date=March 26, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=February 15, 1983 |archive-date=January 20, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240120012038/https://www.nytimes.com/1983/02/15/sports/robinson-is-named-coach-of-rams.html |url-status=live }}</ref> During his time as head coach, Robinson led the team to six playoff berths and one division title. He is still the Rams' leader in years as head coach (9), regular season games coached (143), and regular season loses (68).<ref>{{cite news |title=Rams' Sean McVay Makes 'Promise' That He'll Coach '24 Season |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/rams-sean-mcvay-makes-promise-hell-coach-24/story?id=106049257 |access-date=January 24, 2024 |agency=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |date=January 2, 2024 |archive-date=January 3, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240103233120/https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/rams-sean-mcvay-makes-promise-hell-coach-24/story?id=106049257 |url-status=live }}</ref> After a {{win–loss record|w=3|l=13}} finish in 1991, Robinson was fired and Knox was rehired as head coach where he remained with the team for three seasons prior to the Rams' relocation to St. Louis.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kawakami |first1=Tim |title=Robinson Era Ends with a Thud |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-12-23-sp-765-story.html |access-date=January 24, 2024 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=December 23, 1991 |archive-date=January 26, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240126013327/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-12-23-sp-765-story.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=NFL Notes: Floundering Rams Dump Coach Knox |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/NFL-NOTES-Floundering-Rams-Dump-Coach-Knox-3048640.php |access-date=January 24, 2024 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=January 10, 1995 |archive-date=January 26, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240126014122/https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/NFL-NOTES-Floundering-Rams-Dump-Coach-Knox-3048640.php |url-status=live }}</ref>

For the Rams' first two seasons in St. Louis, [[Rich Brooks]] served as head coach before being replaced by [[Dick Vermeil]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shapiro |first1=Leonard |title=Vermeil Confident After 15-Year Lapse |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/01/22/vermeil-confident-after-15-year-lapse/ab006190-1f7d-4cae-98d3-5fdfae8e7c32/ |access-date=March 26, 2023 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=January 22, 1997}}</ref> Despite two consecutive seasons where the team finished last in its division, Vermeil alongside a rejuvenated offense nicknamed [[The Greatest Show on Turf]] led the Rams to victory in [[Super Bowl XXXIV]] at the end of the [[1999 NFL season]], marking the franchise's first Super Bowl title.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Baskin |first1=Ben |title=How Mike Martz and The Greatest Show on Turf Kicked Off an NFL revolution |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2017/05/23/rams-greatest-show-on-turf-mike-martz-dick-vermeil |access-date=September 26, 2023 |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=May 23, 2017 |archive-date=October 9, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231009003350/https://www.si.com/nfl/2017/05/23/rams-greatest-show-on-turf-mike-martz-dick-vermeil |url-status=live }}</ref> Upon Vermeil's retirement at the conclusion of the aforementioned season, offensive coordinator [[Mike Martz]] was named his replacement, leading the Rams to four playoff berths in five seasons, including an NFC Championship and an appearance in [[Super Bowl XXXVI]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Renaud |first1=Josh |title=Mike Martz |url=https://www.stltoday.com/mike-martz/article_78ec7350-efb8-5b0c-9d8f-6b062a213656.html |access-date=March 24, 2022 |work=St. Louis Post Dispatch |date=January 30, 2010 |archive-date=November 20, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211120202014/https://www.stltoday.com/mike-martz/article_78ec7350-efb8-5b0c-9d8f-6b062a213656.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Rams Coaches" /> After Martz took a medical leave of absence five games into the [[2005 NFL season]], assistant coach [[Joe Vitt]] was hired as his replacement for the remainder of the season.<ref name="SI 2005">{{cite magazine |last1=Silver |first1=Michael |title=Fallen Idols |url=https://vault.si.com/vault/2005/11/21/fallen-idols |access-date=February 7, 2022 |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=November 21, 2005 |archive-date=May 29, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220529112254/https://vault.si.com/vault/2005/11/21/fallen-idols |url-status=live }}</ref> From that point on through 2016, the Rams entered a 12-year period of poor results under the leadership of head coaches [[Scott Linehan]], [[Steve Spagnuolo]], and [[Jeff Fisher]], with the latter's tenure occurring during the team's return to Los Angeles. Linehan, Spagnuolo, and Fisher were each fired in midseason, with Vitt, [[Jim Haslett]] and [[John Fassel]] serving as interim head coaches during that period.<ref name="Rams Coaches" /> The Rams franchise's fortunes turned around with the hiring of [[Sean McVay]] as the 28th and current head coach of the team. Upon his hiring in 2017 at the age of 30, he became the youngest head coach in league history.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Klein |first1=Gary |title=Rams Have a New Leading Man in Coach Sean McVay |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/rams/la-sp-rams-sean-mcvay-20170112-story.html |access-date=September 11, 2021 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=January 12, 2017 |archive-date=June 23, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210623004349/https://www.latimes.com/sports/rams/la-sp-rams-sean-mcvay-20170112-story.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In eight seasons, McVay has led the Rams to six playoff berths, four [[NFC West]] Division titles, two NFC Championships, including a loss in [[Super Bowl LIII]] in [[2018 NFL season|2018]] and a victory in [[Super Bowl LVI]] in [[2021 NFL season|2021]].<ref name=McVay>{{cite web |title=Sean McVay |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/coaches/McVaSe0.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=December 10, 2022 |archive-date=February 12, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230212010541/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/coaches/McVaSe0.htm |url-status=live }}</ref> Already the youngest coach to reach the Super Bowl three years earlier, McVay became the youngest head coach to lead a team to a Super Bowl championship.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shpigel |first1=Ben |title=Rams' Aggressive Roster Build Pays Off in Super Bowl Win |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/02/13/sports/football/rams-bengals-score.html |access-date=March 27, 2022 |work=The New York Times |date=February 15, 2022 |archive-date=March 29, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220329102913/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/02/13/sports/football/rams-bengals-score.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2024, McVay became the Rams franchise leader in regular season and overall coaching victories.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=Stu |title=Sean McVay Becomes Winningest Head Coach in Rams Franchise History with Team's Week 8 Victory over Vikings |url=https://www.therams.com/news/sean-mcvay-becomes-winningest-head-coach-in-rams-franchise-history-with-team-s-week-8-victory-over-vikings |access-date=March 24, 2025 |publisher=[[Los Angeles Rams]] |date=October 25, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241105185940/https://www.therams.com/news/sean-mcvay-becomes-winningest-head-coach-in-rams-franchise-history-with-team-s-week-8-victory-over-vikings |archive-date=November 5, 2024 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>

